You couldn't choose the tea and coffee; it came with sugar included... you didn't have the option of bitter or sweetened. On the other hand, I must emphasize that I really enjoyed the show by Piero and Horacio, who made Mother's Day beautiful despite the stinky food and trucks. I know they can turn this around.

I was near Progreso and craving mozzarella. Maps directed me here. The reviews were very appealing, and I decided to try it. When I walked in, it was nighttime and there were no other customers. Naively and ignorantly, I asked if the $220 price on the board was for a meter or half a meter, or what I was getting for that money, to which he replied it was a slice (imagine my face). But it had a LOT of mozzarella!! Almost as an apology, he justified the (to me) high price. In addition to showing me the generous dimensions with the knife (not huge, let's agree), he emphasized that no one in all of Uruguay puts that much! When I also ordered a fain√° (I was going to order two, but at $160 a slice, and having only $400), he showed me the giant slice, more like an airport pennant, and I was convinced that one would be enough...
By then my cravings were adding up to $380, luckily I still had enough money in my pocket.
The mozzarella preparation arrived, and after opening a freezer, those little hands (without tongs or gloves) began to load layers and more layers, until I couldn't take any more, always with the hype of being the best, now almost on the American continent...
There they put my pizza with mozzarella and fain√° in the oven (I think it was the other way around, mozzarella with pizza), and I was happy...
Meanwhile, and to save time, I asked him to charge me, whereupon those same little cheese hands took the money and gave me the change in coins. I thought, will I be the first of the night, or has he already charged another customer before? Well, out of sight... I thought... But I was just watching...!
When it was hot, he takes away my portions and asks if I'd like oregano. I say yes, and also pepper for the fain√°, but he proudly explains that he's already added it! Luckily, I like it with pepper. I don't know how I'd get it out if I didn't like it, or if I were allergic, anyway...
At that point, I wanted to get to my cave to stuff myself with gluttony and enjoy every dollar I'd invested, since it also took me 14 km round trip, being in Canel√≥n Chico!
It arrived, and almost without saying a word (I was alone, hehe), I dug into the first bite and felt like I was drowning in that tide of mozzarella... it was something unique, something I'd never experienced before... Everything went in like a bowling ball, because the melted cheese kept coming together as I chewed... By the second bite, I'd already bitten off a smaller piece, just in case...
The fain√° wasn't like the regular ones; it was like puff pastry, and it didn't even look like the kind served anywhere, nor did it look like it was made from chickpea flour. Added to the added pepper, it was pretty awful to me. Even considering it cost $160, I wouldn't have eaten it with gusto... I wouldn't have been a fan of the mozzarella!!
Speaking of which, I didn't like the tomato sauce at all; it seemed like one of those quick ones, with a taste far removed from what I expected...
Anyway, the next day I had breakfast without fain√°, and I shaved off the mozzarella to reduce the cheese layer by a centimeter or so. My two faithful companions really liked everything I offered them, so in the end I'm a non-conformist!!
This is all MY reality. There's no accounting for taste! Cheers to Diego, aka Kiko!!

All my life buying pizza here, the best pizza in the world without a doubt, I get excited when I remember it. I give a total crack, I have beautiful memories in the pizzeria from all my childhood and going is almost ritualistic, the best pizza in the world and I don't read any tears.
